full_text: @WSJ At low tide, you may view the "Tanah Lot" rock base where the legendary ‘Guardian’ sea snakes dwell in cracks around the "Tirta Pabersihan" fountain.

@WSJ Before continuing his journey, the monk advised the people to build a temple on "Tanah Lot" because according to his sacred inner feelings this was a good place for worship to the "God of the Sea", to invoke the safety and welfare of the world.
@WSJ Gili Beo then changed its name to "Tanah Lot", that means "Land in the sea".
@WSJ Nicknamed "Bali Temple in the Sea", the "Tanah Lot Temple" looks like floating in the middle of the sea during high tide.

@WSJ Located on a large coral rock facing the Indian Ocean, famous for its amazing, beautiful sunsets, "Tanah Lot Temple" is a Hindu temple in Bali, of breathtaking natural beauty, built to worship God in its appearance as "God Baruna", the God of the Sea.
